<button class="accordion">Who gets motor neurone disease?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Motor neurone disease is an uncommon condition that mainly affects people in their 60s and 70s, but can affect adults of all ages. It's caused by a problem with cells in the brain and nerves called motor neurone. These cells gradually stop working overtime.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the chances of getting motor neuron disease?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Those carrying a fault in a gene leading to MND have a 50 per cent (one in two) chance of passing the genetic error on to their children. However, the risk of someone carrying the faulty gene actually developing MND may be lower than 50 per cent in some cases.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why can it take so long to diagnose motor neurone disease?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>MND is a tough condition to diagnose. The Reason for this is that few cases of MND follow exactly the same pattern. Because MND is relatively rare, patients may have been referred to various specialists before seeing a neurologist.There are currently no specific tests for MND. Where tests are carried out, these are used to rule out other conditions.
